{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492719"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:42:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:42:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1139"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1139"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.1,0.02,0.49,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1139"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80328"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1139"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1139"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65597"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"842"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27450"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80328"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of colicky lower abdominal pain associated with vomiting and diarrhoea. She recently immigrated from Argentina. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly unwell. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is slightly distended but soft to palpation with mild generalised tenderness. A plain abdominal radiograph is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the calcified lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Faecolith","Gallstone","Kidney stone","Hydatid disease","Tuberculosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe abdominal radiograph shows a characteristic rim-calcified lesion in the region of the left lobe of the liver. Given the patient\u0027s origin from Argentina, where \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/em\u003E is endemic, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydatid disease\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. Hydatid cysts typically develop a calcified rim over time and are most commonly found in the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efaecolith\u003C/strong\u003E would typically appear as a small (\u0026lt;1cm) partially calcified lesion in the right iliac fossa, not in the upper abdomen as seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGallstones\u003C/strong\u003E are only radiopaque in approximately 20% of cases and are typically smaller (\u0026lt;1cm) and located in the right upper quadrant. The size and location of this lesion make gallstones unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKidney stones\u003C/strong\u003E can be visible on plain radiographs but are usually smaller and would be expected at the level of L2-3 or below, not in the upper abdomen where this lesion is located.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E of the liver can present either as miliary TB with multiple small calcified lesions, or as macronodular TB with chunky internal calcifications. The single lesion with rim calcification seen here is not typical of hepatic tuberculosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHydatid disease is caused by the tapeworm \u003Cem\u003EE. granulosus\u003C/em\u003E and is endemic in many parts of the world including South America, Eastern Europe, the Middle East, and parts of Asia. Most hydatid cysts are found in the liver and are often asymptomatic until they become large or cause complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydatid cysts characteristically show rim calcification on plain radiographs","Hydatid disease should be considered in patients from endemic regions including South America, Eastern Europe, Middle East, and parts of Asia","Most hydatid cysts are found in the liver and are often asymptomatic until large"],"references":["Kakkar C, Polnaya AM, Koteshwara P, Smiti S, Rajagopal KV, Arora A. Hepatic tuberculosis: a multimodality imaging review. Insights Imaging. 2015;6(6):647-658. doi:10.1007/s13244-015-0440-y","Bortoff GA, Chen MY, Ott DJ, Wolfman NT, Routh WD. Gallbladder stones: imaging and intervention. Radiographics. 2000 May-Jun;20(3):751-66. doi: 10.1148/radiographics.20.3.g00ma16751. PMID: 10835126."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65597"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1139"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18439"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20399"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18439"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bd229f30-7028-4ae0-ab7b-35595d38e132.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bd229f30-7028-4ae0-ab7b-35595d38e132.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":340,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"20399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20399"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/OjT1Kuzhfu4nZ6ykug8IZDOtnHAyap.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/OjT1Kuzhfu4nZ6ykug8IZDOtnHAyap.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":340,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions